{"summary":"All three amendments identify real integrity defects in the filesystem-backed milestone/task-run model. Accepting them improves namespace safety and prevents lineage corruption or contradictory run history.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-16-381b2bc1","decision":"accept","rationale":"`MilestoneId::new()` currently allows hidden names other than `.` and `..`, while milestone listing already skips dot-prefixed directories and lock storage now reserves `milestones/.locks/`. That makes `.locks` a concrete path collision and makes any dot-prefixed milestone effectively invisible to normal enumeration. Rejecting dot-prefixed IDs is a simple, durable invariant."},{"amendment_id":"fr-16-20005d1b","decision":"accept","rationale":"When `run_id` is supplied, finalization should target only that exact attempt. The current fallback from a missing exact match to the sole unfinished runless row is no longer safely disambiguated because `record_bead_completion` no longer uses `started_at`. That can attach a new named retry’s completion to an older open attempt and corrupt the audit trail. Failing fast is the safer behavior; same-attempt repair should happen through start replay, where `started_at` is still available."},{"amendment_id":"fr-16-20943f79","decision":"accept","rationale":"Starting a new explicit `run_id` while an older runless row remains open leaves contradictory lineage: `find_runs_for_bead` can report one attempt still `running` even though a later retry already finished. That is inconsistent with the rest of the code, which already treats mixed open legacy/named states as ambiguous in other paths. The start path should either supersede the stale legacy attempt or reject the new start until the old row is resolved."}]}